## 2. Business Model — The CRO Engine

EFG's entire competitive identity is built around one structural differentiator: the Client Relationship Officer model. Unlike most private banks that centralise advisory, EFG gives each CRO full ownership of their client relationships. CROs are hired with their books. When they join EFG, their clients tend to follow.

**How the model works:**
- Each CRO manages an average book of CHF 240m+ in AuM
- CROs act entrepreneurially — they are partners, not employees in the traditional sense
- Revenue is directly tied to CRO headcount, productivity, and retention
- The bank grows organically by hiring CROs away from competitors and inorganically by acquiring smaller banks and absorbing their CRO teams

**The model's strength is also its vulnerability.** Because each CRO relationship is personal and non-transferable, the bank is highly exposed to CRO attrition. A CRO who leaves takes their clients. A CRO who is unproductive drags revenue. A CRO who is burdened by operational overhead produces less. This is precisely why the 2026–2028 strategy centres on "augmenting" CROs rather than replacing or restructuring them.

**CRO productivity metrics (2024–2025):**
- Average AuM per CRO: CHF 348m (end-2024), up from CHF 321m (end-2023)
- 73 new CROs hired in 2024; target is 50–70 per year through 2028
- 763 total CROs as of end-2025 (up 8.5% year-on-year, partly from acquisitions)
- Mandate penetration: 67% (October 2025); target is 70–75% by end-2028

The mandate penetration gap is the single most important commercial metric to understand. Each 1% increase in mandate penetration represents higher-margin, recurring advisory revenue. Getting from 67% to 75% requires CROs to spend more time advising and less time administering. Technology is the only lever that achieves this without hiring proportionally more staff.

