## 7. Strengths

Understanding EFG's genuine strengths is as important as its challenges — the pitch must show respect for what they have built.

### Strength 1: Consistent Strategic Execution
EFG has delivered on every three-year strategic plan it has set since 2019. In the 2023–2025 cycle, it met or exceeded all major targets — profit growth, NNA growth, cost/income improvement, and RoTE. This is not a bank in trouble; it is a bank that has earned the right to be ambitious.

### Strength 2: The CRO Model Works
The proof is in the numbers. CROs hired in 2023 and 2024 contributed significantly to 2024 NNA inflows. Average AuM per CRO is growing year-on-year. The model's self-reinforcing logic — hire the best advisors, give them the best platform, let them bring clients — has produced genuine compounding growth.

### Strength 3: Strong Capital Position
EFG's CET1 ratio is 17.1%, its total capital ratio is 20.6%, and its liquidity coverage ratio is 255% (as of H1 2025). This is a conservatively capitalised bank with genuine balance sheet strength, giving it the capacity to fund both M&A and technology investment simultaneously.

### Strength 4: Geographic Diversification
Unlike many Swiss private banks that are heavily concentrated in European HNW clients, EFG has meaningful presence across Asia Pacific (strong net new assets from APAC, "Employer of the Year" in Asia 2025), the Americas (Latin America growth driven by Quilvest, Panama office), and the Middle East. This diversification insulates it from single-market downturns and provides multiple growth vectors.

### Strength 5: Open Architecture Product Model
EFG has committed to an open-architecture investment approach — it does not push proprietary products. The Capital Group partnership (February 2026) is the most recent expression of this. This makes EFG attractive to sophisticated HNW clients who want access to best-in-class external managers rather than being sold a bank's own funds.

### Strength 6: Brand and Employer Positioning
EFG has earned "Great Place to Work" certification in Switzerland and "Employer of the Year" at the Asian Private Banker Awards in 2025. For a bank whose growth depends on attracting top CRO talent, this is a meaningful competitive advantage.

